                    <div align="left"><br />
                      &quot;Few of us who live in cities, besieged by flights of what we like to call winged rats, can rightly be described as philoperisterons. But King George the Fifth of England was. So was Charles Darwin. Julius Reuter was too, though for purely commercial reasons. And so also, and for which we should all be thankful, is Andrew Blechman, writer. Mr. Blechman positively loves pigeons - but as graceful and ancient grey doves, not as either targets or as food. In this breezy, quirky, endlessly entertaining book, he tells us just why - and explains why philoperisteronicism is, generally speaking, a Good Thing.&quot; </div>
                  </div>
                  <p>&mdash;Simon Winchester, author of The Professor and The Madman </p>
                <!-- InstanceEndEditable --></td>
              </tr>
